<!-- ── SECTION 1: THE NUMBERS ──────────────── -->
<div class="section">
  <p class="section-label">The Hard Numbers First</p>
  <h2>Before the Opinion — The Data</h2>

  <p>Let's start where the WhatsApp forwards never do: with verified, sourced statistics that explain exactly how exposed India is — and exactly how much the government has already done about it.</p>

  <div class="stat-strip">
    <div class="stat-cell">
      <div class="stat-num red">88%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Of India's crude oil is imported. We make almost none ourselves.</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Source: Ministry of Petroleum, Rajya Sabha, March 2026</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-cell">
      <div class="stat-num amber">5.5M</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Barrels of crude oil India consumes every single day</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Source: India Briefing / MoP&NG, March 2026</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-cell">
      <div class="stat-num white">$110B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Spent on oil imports in just 11 months of FY 2025–26</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Source: Rajya Sabha data, March 2026</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-cell">
      <div class="stat-num blue">41</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Countries India now sources crude from — up from 27 a decade ago</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Source: PM Modi, Rajya Sabha address, March 2026</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>And then there's the strait nobody could stop talking about.</p>

  <div class="stat-strip">
    <div class="stat-cell">
      <div class="stat-num red">20M</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Barrels per day transited the Strait of Hormuz in 2025 — 20% of all global oil consumption</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Source: U.S. EIA / IEA, 2025–26</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-cell">
      <div class="stat-num amber">84%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Of all Hormuz crude flows head to Asian markets. Japan, Korea, India, China — all of us.</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Source: U.S. EIA, 2024</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-cell">
      <div class="stat-num red">90%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Of India's LPG imports — your cooking gas — normally passes through the Strait of Hormuz</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Source: PIB, Government of India, March 2026</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-cell">
      <div class="stat-num white">$113</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Price of India's crude basket on March 11, 2026 — up from $62–70 just weeks earlier</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Source: India Briefing, March 2026</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>Over 90% of your cooking gas is imported through one 21-mile-wide chokepoint. That's not a supply chain. That's a single point of failure dressed up as infrastructure.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── SECTION 2: NOT OUR WAR ─────────────── -->
<div class="section">
  <p class="section-label">Context First</p>
  <h2>The War That's Not Ours — But Still Bills Us</h2>

  <p>Let's be unambiguous, because social media has once again confused alarm with information:</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>India is <strong>not</strong> going to war. India is preparing to deal with what war <em>brings</em>. That difference is everything.</p>
  </div>

  <p>The ongoing conflict in West Asia is not India's battlefield. But it sits squarely on India's energy lifeline. Half of our oil imports — 2.6 million barrels a day — were coming from Gulf countries that route through the Strait of Hormuz. When Operation Epic Fury was launched on February 28, 2026, and Iran effectively closed the strait, India didn't just face a news headline. It faced a supply chain emergency in slow motion.</p>

  <div class="pull-quote">
    <p>The war isn't knocking at your door. It's quietly letting itself into your monthly budget and rearranging the furniture.</p>
  </div>

  <p>No soldier. No siren. No drama. Just energy prices, supply tightening, and inflation — the slowest, sneakiest casualty of someone else's conflict. The tanker war-risk insurance premium surged over <strong>500%</strong> overnight. That cost doesn't stay at sea. It lands in your grocery bill.</p>

  <p>And yet — India was not caught entirely flat-footed. Here's what changed fast.</p>

  <div class="data-row">
    <div class="data-big">70%</div>
    <div class="data-text">Of India's crude imports now arrive via routes <em>outside</em> the Strait of Hormuz — up from 55% just before the crisis. The government pivoted in real time.
    <em>Source: Ministry of Petroleum Joint Secretary, Inter-Ministerial Briefing, March 11, 2026</em></div>
  </div>
  <div class="data-row">
    <div class="data-big">25%</div>
    <div class="data-text">Increase in domestic LPG production after government issued emergency orders diverting propane and butane streams to household supply.
    <em>Source: PIB Press Release, March 2026</em></div>
  </div>
  <div class="data-row">
    <div class="data-big">74 days</div>
    <div class="data-text">India's combined oil reserve buffer — strategic reserves + OMC commercial stocks. The IEA recommends 90. We're at 74. Not perfect, but not helpless.
    <em>Source: FM Nirmala Sitharaman, March 2026</em></div>
  </div>
  <div class="data-row">
    <div class="data-big">28</div>
    <div class="data-text">Indian-flagged vessels currently operating in the Persian Gulf, with 778 Indian seafarers onboard. All monitored 24×7 by a dedicated government control room.
    <em>Source: Directorate General of Shipping, March 2026</em></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── SECTION 3: SCENARIOS ───────────────── -->
<div class="section">
  <p class="section-label">Risk Mapping</p>
  <h2>How Bad Can This Get? Three Scenarios, No Hysteria.</h2>

  <p>Let's run the scenarios like adults — not like prime-time news anchors whose job is to keep you watching.</p>

  <div class="scenarios">
    <div class="scenario">
      <div class="snum">01</div>
      <span class="stag tl">Most Likely</span>
      <h4>Prolonged Conflict</h4>
      <p>Oil prices stay elevated. HSBC estimates a 25-bps GDP drag if gas supply shortfall lasts one quarter. Inflation creeps. Life continues, with tighter margins and more creative household budgeting.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="scenario">
      <div class="snum">02</div>
      <span class="stag tp">Possible</span>
      <h4>Regional Escalation</h4>
      <p>Supply chains get disrupted further. Industrial gas cuts (already underway at 35% for refineries) widen. Fertiliser production affected. Food prices follow. Painful, but manageable.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="scenario">
      <div class="snum">03</div>
      <span class="stag te">Tail Risk</span>
      <h4>Sustained Closure</h4>
      <p>Trade routes blocked for months. Global oil shock. India's 74-day buffer gets tested. Our Americas/Russia pivot becomes load-bearing. This is the scenario the government is quietly preparing for.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>Notice the common thread. None of these scenarios involve Indian troops. All of them involve Indian households. <strong>The battlefield is economic. So your preparation should be too.</strong></p>

  <div class="amber-note">
    <p>India currently holds ~332 million active LPG connections. The domestic LPG system has roughly 18 days of inventory cover. That buffer is useful against short disruptions — but it is not designed for a sustained blockade. This is why the government moved to maximize domestic LPG production immediately.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── SECTION 4: GOVT ACTIONS ────────────── -->
<div class="section">
  <p class="section-label">What's Actually Happening</p>
  <h2>The Government's War Room. Here's the Actual Inventory.</h2>

  <p>This is where it gets interesting — and more reassuring than the noise suggests. PM Modi addressed both Houses of Parliament. Seven empowered inter-ministerial groups have been constituted. Here's what's actually been deployed:</p>

  <ul class="act-list">
    <li>
      <strong>24×7 Energy Control Room</strong>
      A round-the-clock monitoring system for petroleum stocks, vessel movements, and fuel availability has been operational since February 28, 2026. Not theatre. Actual infrastructure.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Natural Gas Control Order — March 9, 2026</strong>
      Invoked under the Essential Commodities Act. CNG and domestic PNG: 100% supply. Tea and manufacturing industries: 80% of average. Fertiliser plants: 70%. Refineries and petrochemicals: 65% — to protect household priority.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>LPG Maximisation Order — March 8, 2026</strong>
      All refineries and petrochemical units directed to divert propane, butane, and butenes to the LPG pool. Result: domestic LPG production up 25%. Entire domestic output redirected to household consumers.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Energy Pivot to 41 Supplier Countries</strong>
      India is actively securing crude from USA, Nigeria, Angola, Canada, Colombia, Brazil, and Mexico — in addition to Russia, which accounts for roughly one-third of current imports. New LNG cargoes sourced and en route.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Strategic Petroleum Reserve Status</strong>
      SPR at 64% capacity — 3.372 MMT out of 5.33 MMT — providing roughly 9.5 days of emergency cover (at full capacity). Phase II expansion approved: Chandikhol and Padur additions will add 6.5 MMT. Completion: 2030.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Diplomatic Multi-Alignment</strong>
